06591nam a22008295i 9780774828949DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20152015xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748289497 a10.59962/97807748289492doi  a(DE-B1597)662061  a(OCoLC)900656283  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aHIS0540002bisacsh04a907.2qOCoLC223/eng/2023021600aBeyond Testimony and Trauma :bOral History in the Aftermath of Mass Violence /ced. by Steven High. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (388 p.) :b7 photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aShared: Oral and Public History00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tThe Political Work of Witness -- tThe Ex-Disappeared in Post-Dictatorship Argentina -- tPessimism of the Intellect, Optimism of the Will -- tThe Ethics of Learning from Rwandan Survivor Communities -- tThe Role of Oral History in Surviving a Eugenic Past -- tWorking with Survivors -- tFrom Testimony to Recounting -- tCollaborative Witnessing and Sharing Authority in Conversations with Holocaust Survivors -- tSharing “A Big Kettle of Soup” -- t“Questions Are More Important than Answers” -- tOn Tour with Mapping Memories -- tActs of Composure and Framing -- tEconomic Violence, Occupational Disability, and Death -- tThe Frames We Use -- tMemories of Departures -- tFinding Meaning in Oral History Sources through Storytelling and Religion -- tAfterword -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSurvivors of terrible events are often portrayed as unsung heroes or tragic victims but rarely as complex human beings whose lives extend beyond the stories they have told. Beyond Testimony and Trauma considers other ways to engage with survivors and their accounts based on insights gained from long-term oral history projects in a variety of contexts, including factory closures, industrial injury, eugenics and forced sterilization, the Holocaust, genocide in Rwanda and Cambodia, Argentinian torture camps, the Yugoslav Wars, and Jewish emigration from the Maghreb. The contributors, all innovators in the field of oral history, include Henry Greenspan who provides reflections from forty years of listening to Holocaust survivors as well as an insightful afterword. They demonstrate that – through deep listening, long-term relationship building, and collaborative research design – it is possible to move beyond the problematic aspects of “testimony” to shine light on the more nuanced lives of survivors of mass violence. In the process, they offer alternative approaches to the collection of oral history that will shake the foundations of current historiographical practice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aOral biography. 0aOral history. 0aSurvival. 0aVictims. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh1 aBaker, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Yolande, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEllis, Carolyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFournier, Sara Cohen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGandsman, Ari, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreenspan, Henry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHigh, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHigh, Steven, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLuchs, Michele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcIvor, Arthur, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabular